# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: balut-food
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] The cooking method for the Philippine *adobo* is indigenous to the Philippines.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] The various precolonial peoples of the Philippine archipelago often cooked or prepared their food with vinegar and salt in various techniques to preserve them in the tropical climate.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] Vinegar, in particular, is one of the most important ingredients in Filipino cuisine, with the main traditional types being coconut, cane, nipa palm, and kaong palm.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] These are all linked to traditional alcohol fermentation.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] It is believed that paksíw, sangkutsá, and *adobo* are all derivations of *kiniláw*.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] They are also related to cooking techniques like *sinigáng* and *pinangát na isdâ* that also have a sour broth, albeit using fruits like calamansi, tamarind, unripe mangoes, bilimbi, *santól*, and star fruit as souring agents instead of vinegar.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] When the Spanish Empire colonized the Philippines in the late 16th and early 17th centuries, they encountered the *adobo* cooking process.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] It was first recorded in the 1613 dictionary *Vocabulario de la lengua tagala* compiled by the Spanish Franciscan missionary, Pedro de San Buenaventura.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] He referred to it as *adobo de los naturales* ("*adobo* of the native [peoples]").
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] The Spanish also applied the term *adobo* to any native dish that was marinated before consumption.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] However, the concept of cooking *adobo* already existed long before the arrival of the Spanish in 1521.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] In the 1794 edition of the *Vocabulario*, it was applied to *quilauìn* (*kinilaw*) a related but different dish which also primarily uses vinegar.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] In the 1711 Visayan dictionary *Vocabulario de la lengua Bisaya*, the term *guinamus* (verb form: *gamus*) was used to refer to any kind of marinades (*adobo*), from fish to pork.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] Other terms for precolonial *adobo*-like dishes among the Visayan peoples are *dayok* and *danglusi*.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] In modern Visayan, *guinamós* and *dayok* refer to separate dishes.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] Dishes prepared with vinegar, garlic, salt (later soy sauce), and other spices eventually came to be known solely as *adobo*, with the original term for the dish now lost to history.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] While the Filipino *adobo* and Spanish style *adobo* share vinegar and garlic, they are culturally distinct dishes with different ingredients and culinary traditions.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] Unlike Spanish and Latin American adobo, Philippine *adobo* does not traditionally use chilis, paprika, oregano, or tomatoes.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] Instead, they only share similarities in their primary use of vinegar and garlic.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] Philippine *adobo* has a characteristically salty and sour, and often sweet taste, in contrast to Spanish and Mexican *adobos*, which are spicier or infused with oregano.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] While the Philippine *adobo* can be considered *adobo* in the Spanish sense—a marinated dish—the Philippine usage is much more specific to a cooking process (rather than a specific recipe) and is not restricted to meat.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] Typically, pork or chicken, or a combination of both, is slowly cooked in vinegar, crushed garlic, bay leaves, black peppercorns, and soy sauce.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] It was traditionally cooked in small clay pots (*palayok* or *kulon*); but today, metal pots or woks (*kawali*) are largely used instead.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] There are numerous variants of the *adobo* recipes in the Philippines.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] The most basic ingredient of *adobo* is vinegar, which is usually coconut vinegar, rice vinegar, or cane vinegar (although sometimes white wine or cider vinegar can also be used).
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] Almost every ingredient can be changed according to personal preference.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] Even people in the same household can cook *adobo* in significantly different ways.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] A rarer version without soy sauce is known as *adobong puti* ("white *adobo*"), which uses salt instead, to contrast it with *adobong itim* ("black *adobo*"), the more prevalent versions with soy sauce.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] *Adobong puti* is often regarded as the closest to the original version of the prehispanic adobo.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] It is similar to another dish known as *pinatisan*, where *patis* (fish sauce) is used instead of vinegar.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] The proportion of ingredients like soy sauce, bay leaves, garlic, or black pepper can vary.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] The amount and thickness of the sauce also varies as some like their *adobo* dry while some like it saucy.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] Other ingredients can sometimes be used; like *siling labuyo*, bird's eye chili, jalapeño pepper, red bell pepper, olive oil, onions, brown sugar, potatoes, pineapple, or lemon-lime sodas like Sprite.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] It may also be further browned in the oven, pan-fried, deep-fried, or even grilled to get crisped edges.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] Based on the main ingredients, the most common *adobo* types are *adobong manok*, in which chicken is used, and *adobong baboy*, in which pork is used.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] *Adobong baka* (beef), along with *adobong manok* (chicken), is more popular among Muslim Filipinos in accordance with halal dietary laws.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] Other meats may also be used, such as *pugò* (quail), *itik* (duck), and *kambíng* (goat).
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] Seafood variants include fish (*isdâ*), catfish (*hitò*), shrimp (*hipon*), and squid or cuttlefish (*pusít*).
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] Vegan options utilize vegetables and fruits, like water spinach (*kangkóng*), bamboo shoots (*labóng*), eggplant (*talóng*), banana flowers (*pusô ng saging*), and okra (*okra*).
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] Offal and giblets can also be cooked as *adobo*, like liver, gizzard, heart, and neck.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] Other versions include *adobong sawâ* (snake), *adobong palakâ* (frog), Kapampangan *adobung kamaru* (mole cricket), and the *adobong atáy at balúnbalunan* (chicken liver and gizzard).
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] In Bicol, Quezon, and south in Zamboanga City, it is common for *adobo* to have coconut milk (known as *adobo sa gatâ*).
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] In Batangas and Laguna, turmeric is added, giving the dish a distinct, yellowish color (known as *adobong dilaw*, "yellow *adobo*"), as well as a red variant using *achuete* seeds in the former.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] In the northernmost province of Batanes, the Ivatan prepare a type of *adobo* called *luñiz*, where they preserve pork in jars with salt.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] Outside of the dish itself, the flavor of *adobo* has been developed commercially and adapted to other foods.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] A number of local Philippine snack products such as cornicks, nuts, chips, noodle soups, and corn crackers, market their items as "*adobo* flavored".
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] In 2021, the Bureau of Philippine Standards of the Department of Trade and Industry (DTI-BPS) of the Philippines unveiled plans to standardize the most popular Filipino dishes to make it easier to promote them internationally as well as keep their cultural identity.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] Philippine *adobo* will be the first of such dishes to be standardized.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] The definition will be set by a technical committee headed by Glenda Rosales Barreto, and includes representatives from the academia, government departments, the food industry, chefs, and food writers.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] The main reference will be *Kulinarya: A Guidebook to Philippine Cuisine* (2008), authored by Barreto and the committee vice-chairperson Myrna Segismundo, both notable chefs of Filipino cuisine in their own right.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] The announcement has received some criticism from the public, but the DTI-BPS clarified that it's not mandatory and will only aim to define a basic traditional recipe that can serve as a benchmark for determining the authenticity of Filipino dishes in the international setting.
[src:balut-food/adobo-filipino-cuisine] On March 15, 2023, Google Doodles released a Philippine Adobo doodle.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] After leaving Queen's College, Oxford, in 1948, Davidson joined the British diplomatic service, rising through the ranks to conclude his career as ambassador to Laos, from 1973 to 1975.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] He retired early and devoted himself to full-time writing about food, encouraged by Elizabeth David and others.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] He published more than a dozen books between his retirement and 2002, but his *magnum opus* was *The Oxford Companion to Food*, a work of more than a million words, which took twenty years to complete and was published to international acclaim in 1999.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] Davidson was born in Derry, Northern Ireland, the son of William John Davidson (1899–1959), inspector of taxes, and his wife, Constance, *née* Eaton (1889–1974).
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] He was brought up in Leeds in the north-east of England, where he attended Leeds Grammar School.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] His higher education was interrupted by the Second World War, during which he joined the Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve as an ordinary seaman and saw wartime and post-war service in the Mediterranean, Atlantic and Pacific, ending the war as a commissioned officer.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] In 1946 he returned to England to complete his interrupted education at Queen's College, Oxford, where he took a double first in classical moderations and Greats in 1948.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] From Oxford, Davidson joined the Foreign Office and between 1948 and 1973 he served in diplomatic posts in Washington, The Hague, Cairo and Tunis, headed two Foreign Office departments in London, and served as head of chancery in the British delegation to NATO in Brussels.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] There were three daughters of the marriage.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] Davidson concluded his Foreign Office career as British ambassador to Laos, 1973–1975.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] Davidson took early retirement from the diplomatic service at the age of 51 in 1975.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] While the Davidsons were living in Tunis, Jane asked her husband to look for a cookery book on fish because she did not recognise any of the local varieties and was unsure how they should be cooked.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] Not being able to find one he wrote one himself: *Seafish of Tunisia and the Central Mediterranean* "a handbook giving the names of 144 species in 5 languages, with a list of molluscs, crustaceans, and other marine creatures, and notes on cooking".
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] It was a 126-page tract produced on a stencil duplicator and published in 1963.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] Within four years the book had become "a classic", according to *The Times*: "a masterly combination of reference book and cook book with a beautifully illustrated and annotated catalogue of fish, plus a collection of remarkable recipes".
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] Further books on the same lines followed, much of the information in them supplied by Davidson's diplomatic contacts: *Fish and Fish Dishes of Laos* (1975), *Seafood of South-East Asia* (1976), and *North Atlantic Seafood* (1979), all of which went through several editions.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] The same year the Davidsons edited and translated a 320-page selection from *Le grand dictionnaire de cuisine* by Alexandre Dumas, published as *Dumas on Food*.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] In 1979 Davidson and his wife set up a publishing company, Prospect Books, to reprint rare cookery books.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] They also started a magazine, *Petits Propos Culinaires* "the first serious periodical dealing with food history" (Levy).
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] In the same year Davidson was Alistair Horne Research Fellow at St Antony's College, Oxford.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] He convened a symposium on food history, in partnership with Theodore Zeldin, which grew into an annual event known since 1981 as the Oxford Symposium on Food and Cookery.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] The Oxford Companion took Davidson twenty years to complete.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] There were contributions from more than fifty writers, but most of the book was written by Davidson.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] Elizabeth David, like the Davidsons, lived in Chelsea, and she made her extensive library available to him.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] Through her he met her favoured specialist booksellers in London and New York who helped him add to his knowledge.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] Davidson died on 2 December 2003 at the Chelsea and Westminster Hospital, London, of heart failure, aged 79; he was survived by his wife and their three daughters.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] Davidson accepted the award of the CMG on his retirement, but later regretted it, deleted mention of it from his *Who's Who* entry and refused further offers of official government recognition.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] In 2003 he received the Erasmus Prize from Queen Beatrix in Amsterdam in recognition of his establishing the Oxford symposium on food and cookery and writing the Oxford Companion.
[src:balut-food/alan-davidson-food-writer] In March 2010 BBC Four broadcast a television documentary called *The Man Who Ate Everything*, a portrait of Alan Davidson by Andrew Graham-Dixon.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] The **American Veterinary Medical Association** (**AVMA**) is an American not-for-profit association founded in 1863 that represents more than 105,000 veterinarians.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] The AVMA provides information resources, continuing education opportunities, publications, and discounts on personal and professional products, programs, and services.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] The AVMA indicates that it lobbies for animal friendly legislation within a framework that supports the use of animals for human purposes (e.g., food, fiber, research, companionship).
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] The AVMA Council on Education is the designated accrediting body for schools of veterinary medicine in the United States.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] The AVMA publishes the *Journal of the American Veterinary Medical Association* (JAVMA) and the *American Journal of Veterinary Research* (AJVR).
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] The AVMA's veterinary student organization is the Student American Veterinary Medical Association (SAVMA).
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] The American Veterinary Medical Association (AVMA) was founded in 1863, when 40 delegates representing seven states met for a convention in New York.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] Originally named the United States Veterinary Medical Association, the USVMA was renamed the AVMA in 1889.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] By 1913, the AVMA consisted of 1,650 members, with membership open only to graduates of accredited veterinary schools.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] As of 2021, the AVMA has more than 97,000 members.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] In addition to treating pets, veterinarians work in a number of fields, such as public health, agriculture, food safety, academics, and the military.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] The AVMA produces policies in response to member requests and stakeholder interest.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] These statements are general and aim to encourage improvement based on the best available scientific evidence.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] The AVMA's policy was adopted after a comprehensive review by a multi-disciplinary, multi-perspective task force of experts that produced an accompanying review of housing for pregnant sows.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] The AVMA has voted on several proposals to take a formal stand against the forced feeding of birds to make foie gras.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] The AVMA has published a welfare implications of foie gras production backgrounder.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] The AVMA has received pushback from many veterinarians for its classification of ventilation shutdown plus (VSD+) as "acceptable under constrained circumstances".
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] Many veterinarians regard the method as cruel and have questioned the justification for the classification.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] In its guidelines, the AVMA relied only on one report from North Carolina State University and argued this gave evidence that VSD+ provided sufficiently limited suffering.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] However, this unpublished report's methodology has been questioned by organizations such as the Animal Welfare Institute for using an untested metric for stress (using heat shock protein 70), containing mathematical errors, having unclear writing, and more.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] Despite the AVMA's Guidelines for the Depopulation of Animals stating that ventilation shutdown plus should only be used as an extermination method in poultry in constrained circumstances, it has become the most common method of exterminating large flocks.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] AVMA argued that "the CSA must be amended so that our nation's animals do not suffer unnecessarily." Due to an interpretation of the law by the Drug Enforcement Administration, veterinarians were not allowed to travel to their off-site animal patients with controlled substances.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] The United States Department of Education has designated the AVMA Council on Education as the accrediting body for schools of veterinary medicine in the United States.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] In this capacity, the AVMA develops and maintains educational standards for these institutions to ensure the qualifications and competency of graduates of veterinary schools.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] Two bodies within AVMA are responsible for veterinary education accreditation: the AVMA Council on Education (COE) and the Committee on Veterinary Technician Education and Activities (CVTEA).
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] The former is responsible for accreditation of veterinary colleges and the latter veterinary technology programs.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] As of 2025, there are 54 AVMA-accredited veterinary colleges, with 31 being in the United States.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] As of 2021, the AVMA accredits veterinary technician programs in all but three U.S. states, one program in Canada, and a number of distance learning programs.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] As of 2025, there are five colleges provisionally accredited by the AVMA.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] As of 2021, the AVMA recognizes 22 veterinary specialty organizations, including American College of Veterinary Anesthesia and Analgesia, American College of Veterinary Surgeons, and American College of Zoological Medicine.
[src:balut-food/american-veterinary-medical-association] The AVMA recognizes 41 distinct veterinary specialties, including anesthesia, behavior, dentistry, parasitology, pathology, pharmacology, and surgery.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Ingredients common to many cultures in East and Southeast Asia include rice, ginger, garlic, sesame seeds, chilis, dried onions, soy, and tofu.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Stir frying, steaming, and deep frying are common cooking methods.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] While rice is common to most Asian cuisines, different varieties are popular in the various regions.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Glutinous rice is ingrained in the culture, religious tradition and national identity of Laos.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Basmati rice is popular in the Indian subcontinent, jasmine rice is often found across Southeast Asia, while long-grain rice is popular in China and short-grain in Japan and Korea.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Curry is a common dish in South Asia, Southeast Asia, and East Asia.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Curry dishes have their origins in the Indian subcontinent.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Countries in Indochina typically use a coconut milk base in their curries; countries in West Asia typically use a yogurt base.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] A heavily influential aspect of Asian culture is the food, especially the various traditional ways of Asian cuisine and cooking.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Although many Asian cultures often share the traditions of bringing the family or group together to socialize or have celebrations over a meal, the various cultures of Asia each developed their own individual ethnic cultural takes on food through the interaction of history, culture, and environment.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Asian cuisine is often associated with multiculturalism with specific foods linked to many different cultures.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Most Central Asian nations have similar cuisines to each other as well as their neighbors, taking many features of the neighboring cuisines of West and East Asia, particularly Iran and Mongolia.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] A dish known as "plov", or "osh", for example, is a widespread variation of pilaf.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] However, many of the same countries use horse meat and mutton as the most common meats, similar to beef.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] In Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan, the cuisine has evolved to meet the needs of a nomad lifestyle.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Kumis is a widespread drink among Turkic peoples, especially in Central Asia.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Central Asia is also noted for being the birthplace of yogurt.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Like kumis, it is widespread among Turkic peoples.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] East Asian cuisine includes Chinese, Hong Kong, Japanese, Korean, Macanese, Mongolian, Taiwanese, and Tibetan food.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Considering this is the most populated region of the world, it has many regional cuisines (especially in China).
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Examples of staple foods include rice, noodles, mung beans, soybeans, seafood (Japan has the highest per capita consumption of seafood), mutton (Mongolia), bok choy (Chinese cabbage), and tea.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] North Asian cuisine is often synonymous with Russian cuisine, due to all of North Asia being a part of the Russian Federation.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] However, some cultures or areas of Siberia have in-depth cuisine, such as the Yakuts (or Sakha) and Yamal cuisine.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Buryats also have their own cuisine, although it is very similar to that of the related Mongolians.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Pelmeni, originally a Permic or Ugric dish, has entered into mainstream Russian cuisine as a well-known dish, but it can still be considered part of the Yamal cuisine for its area of origin.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Some speculate them to be a simplified version of the Chinese wonton.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] In Siberia, pelmeni is frozen outdoors to preserve the meat inside throughout the long winter.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] In Yamal, other types of drying and preservation are common.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Key ingredients in most northern Siberian cuisine include fish and cowberries, sometimes known as lingonberries in Europe and North America.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Yakuts, like many other Turkic-speaking peoples, traditionally enjoy kumis as a common drink.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] South Asian cuisine includes cuisines from the Indian subcontinent.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Food items in this region are generally rich in spices, however it also caters a blend of multi-cuisine culture from all across the world.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Food is flavored with various types of chili, black pepper, cloves, condiments and other herbs and spices, flavored butters and ghee.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] The multitude is inclined more towards the usage of mustard, groundnut, sunflower and soybean oil for cooking.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Usage of refined oil to make puri is quite famous.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Puri bhaji, idli, dosa, dal baati, and litti are among the most popular and representative dishes of Indian cuisines.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Vegetables are generally eaten with a type of bread called chapati, which is the staple food of the region.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Rice is generally taken with dal to moisten it in northern India, or with curd in southern India.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Tea and coffee are prominent all across with the former available at every street corner.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Egg dishes are also available in similar fashion.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Common meats include lamb, goat, fish, and chicken.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] As cattle are considered sacred in Hinduism, beef is less common than in Western cuisines.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Prohibitions against beef extend to the meat of cows, and yaks to some extent.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Pork is considered a haram by all Muslims, and is avoided by some Hindus.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Other minorities also prohibit the use of meat to abjure violence.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Fish is commonly used in South India, Sri Lanka and the Bengal region, i.e.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Bangladesh and the West Bengal state of India.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] The Northern region diet mostly consists of wheat and other major crops.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Southeast Asian cuisine includes a strong emphasis on lightly prepared dishes with a strong aromatic component that features such flavors as citrus and herbs such as lime, coriander/cilantro and basil.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Ingredients in the region contrast with the ones in the East Asian cuisines, substituting fish sauces for sauce and the inclusion of ingredients such as galangal, tamarind and lemongrass.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Cooking methods include a balance of stir-frying, boiling and steaming.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] West Asian cuisine is the cuisine of the various countries and peoples of West Asia.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] The cuisine of the region is diverse while having a degree of homogeneity.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Some commonly used ingredients include olives and olive oil, pitas, honey, sesame seeds, dates, sumac, chickpeas, mint and parsley.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Some popular dishes include kibbeh and shawarma.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Cereals constitute the basis of West Asian diet, both historically and today.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Wheat and rice are the major and preferred sources of staple foods.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Barley is also widely used in the region and maize has become common in some areas as well.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Bread is a universal staple, eaten in one form or another by all classes and groups practically at every meal.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Butter and clarified butter (also known as Semna) are, traditionally, the preferred medium of cooking.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Olive oil is prevalent in the Mediterranean coastal areas.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Christians use it during Lent, when meat and dairy products are excluded, and Jews use it in place of animal fats such as butter to avoid mixing meat and dairy products.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Lamb and mutton have always been the favored meats of West Asia.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Pork is prohibited in both Islam and Judaism, and as such is rarely eaten in the region.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Prominent among the meat preparations are grilled meats, or kebabs.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Meat and vegetable stews, served with rice, bulgur, or bread, are another form of meat preparation in the region.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Vegetables and pulses are the predominant staples of the great majority of the people in the West Asia.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] They are boiled, stewed, grilled, stuffed, and cooked with meat and rice.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Among the green leafy vegetables, many varieties of cabbage, spinach, and chard are widely used.
[src:balut-food/asian-cuisine] Root and bulb vegetables, such as onions and garlic, as well as carrots, turnips, and beets are equally common.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] The length of incubation before the egg is cooked is a matter of local preference, but generally ranges from two to three weeks.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Balut can cause vomiting if not cooked correctly.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] A balut is a fertilized bird egg (usually a duck) that is incubated for a period of 14 to 21 days, depending on the local culture, and then steamed.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] The contents are eaten directly from the shell.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Balut that is incubated for longer periods have a well-developed embryo and the features of the duckling are recognizable.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] The partially developed embryo bones are soft enough to chew and swallow as a whole.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] The mallard duck (*Anas platyrhynchus*), also known as the "Pateros duck", is often used to make balut.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Balut is a renowned dish due to its different developmental stages; some people prefer it when the duck embryo is still largely liquid, while others prefer it when it is more mature and has a chewier texture.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] A combination of savory, gamey, and rich characteristics can be found in the flavor, which makes it an acquired taste that many Filipinos treasure as a culinary treat and a part of their culture.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Balut is common street food in the Philippines, Vietnam, and other localities, and is also sold in stores and malls.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] It is a relatively cheap source of protein and calcium.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Balut was introduced to the Philippines by the Chinese in 1565, and since then balut has been included as a traditional part of the culture.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Wherever Filipinos migrated for work, a large market for balut would develop.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Controversies arose as knowledge of the food spread around the Southeast Asian countries and then globally.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] People have questioned the ethics of eating balut.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Ethical concerns are most often attributed to the presence of a fertilized embryo within the dish, given the fact that the egg has not yet hatched nor been given the chance to hatch.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] There are also ethical concerns as to whether the embryos can feel pain at the stages balut tends to be boiled.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Traditionally, the fertilized eggs are incubated in the sun or buried in sand and stored in baskets to retain warmth.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] In order for the embryo to develop normally, it must be exposed to heat for the correct period of time while ensuring that the temperature is not too hot to harm the eggs or too cold to permit growth.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] The embryo is extremely sensitive to high temperatures and is easily killed upon cooking in the sun.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Within the first few stages of maturation, balut is known as "balut sa puti" ("wrapped in white") when it is white; the embryo inside is insufficiently developed to show a beak, feathers, or claws, and the bones are undeveloped.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] These are made from very specific egg types, less than five days old and with no visible surface cracks.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] The duration of egg incubation is a matter of local preference.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] In the Philippines, balut is generally incubated for 14 to 18 days before being boiled for consumption.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] At about 14 to 16 days of incubation, the embryo floats on top of the egg white and yolk, and the balut is called "mamatong".
[src:balut-food/balut-food] For most balut makers, the ideal incubation is said to be 17 days old.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] In the Cambodian version, *pong tea khon*, the egg is incubated for 18 to 20 days.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] In the Vietnamese version, *trứng vịt lộn*, the egg is incubated for 19 to 21 days, when the embryo is old enough to be recognizable as a baby duck and has bones that will be firm but tender when cooked.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] During this cooking process, changes occur in the food chemistry of balut, such as the sol dispersion of water molecules within the embryonic fluid.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] This liquid becomes the broth for the solid which are parts of the duck within the egg.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Although balut mainly consists of protein, fat is present and is emulsified within the fertilized embryo.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] After cooking, it can be considered a protein gel, depending on the length of time it was cooked.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Heating high-protein food such as balut can cause the chemical changes to take place and fully or partially denature proteins, causing the surface to become thick and causing an irreversible gel protein to form.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Temperature has a significant impact on the final taste and texture of the cooked balut.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Warm temperatures of 29–30 °C (84–86 °F) change the taste and texture of the yolk by making it more grainy.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] This can be attributed to the changes in proteins, and their partial denaturation, during the heating and incubation process.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] When boiling or cooking eggs, the white of the egg tends to solidify because the proteins are denatured in an irreversible reaction and turn from transparent to an opaque white.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Physical and chemical changes in the final balut product can also be attributed to microbial infections and the rate that microbes infect the balut at various stages.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] There are many chemical changes that occur inside the duck egg as it is being processed, which can vary depending on how or what it is cooked with.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] While boiling, added salt can contribute to a number of chemical changes; it seems to increase the proportional weight of egg white within the shell, which can be due to the weight differences between the embryo and the egg white itself.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Added salt can also increase the hardness of the egg yolk and affect the overall texture of the final balut product.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Other chemical changes observed in nutrient content of the duck egg as it is processed are a slight decrease in the amount of available amino acids, water-soluble vitamins, and minerals after the processing is complete.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] There are different nutritional values for balut, since it can be either fertilized chicken or duck eggs.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Balut nutrition specifications between chicken and duck have minor differences, but both eggs have around 14 grams of crude protein, 188 calories each, and around 100 milligrams of calcium.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] A duck egg might have a higher value of nutrition than a chicken egg, but overall, both chicken and duck balut have approximately the same nutritional value.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] In folk medicine, according to popular Vietnamese belief, these eggs are nutritious and restorative food for pregnant or delivering women.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Balut eggs are savored for their balance of textures and flavors.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] The broth surrounding the embryo is often sipped from the egg before the shell is peeled, then the yolk and young chick inside can be eaten.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] All of the contents of the egg may be consumed, although the white albumen may remain uneaten, depending on the age of the fertilized egg.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] This white albumen may have an unappetizing cartilaginous taste and is tough and rubbery in texture.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] In the Philippines, balut has recently entered *haute cuisine* by being served as appetizers in restaurants, cooked adobo style, fried in omelettes, or even used as filling in baked pastries.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] In Vietnam, balut is eaten with a pinch of pepper salt with lime/kumquat or ginger and rau răm (also known as laksa leaf).
[src:balut-food/balut-food] The dish "trứng vịt lộn" can be served as boiled balut or grilled balut.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] In Cambodia, balut is eaten while still warm in the shell and served with nothing more than a little garnish, which is usually a mixture of lime juice and ground pepper.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] A similar preparation is known in China as *maodan* (Chinese: 毛蛋; pinyin: *máo dàn*; lit.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] 'feathered egg'), *modan* (Chinese: 末蛋; pinyin: *mò dàn*; lit.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] 'end-stage egg'), *wangjidan* (Chinese: 旺雞蛋; pinyin: *wàng jīdàn*; lit.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] 'flush egg'), or *huozhuzi* (Chinese: 活珠子; pinyin: *huózhūzi*; lit.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Chinese traders and migrants are said to have brought the idea of eating fertilized duck eggs to the Philippines; however, the knowledge and craft of balut-making has been localized by the balut-makers (*magbabalut*).
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Today, balut production has not been mechanized in favor of the traditional production by hand.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Many vendors sell cooked balut from buckets of sand (used to retain warmth) accompanied by small packets of salt.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Uncooked balut are rarely sold in Southeast Asia.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] In the United States, Asian markets occasionally carry uncooked balut eggs.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Alternatively, they can be ordered by mail.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] The cooking process is identical to that of hard-boiled chicken eggs, and baluts are eaten while still warm.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Duck eggs that are not properly developed after nine to twelve days are sold as *penoy*, which look, smell, and taste similar to a regular hard-boiled egg.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] In Filipino cuisine, these are occasionally beaten and fried, similar to scrambled eggs, and served with a vinegar dip.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Balut is consumed in high amounts within countries in Southeast Asia, including Laos, Cambodia, Vietnam, Thailand, and the Philippines.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Pateros is a first-class municipality in metro Manila, Philippines, that is famous for its duck-raising industry and balut production.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] The Pateros municipality was actually named for its duck farmers by speakers of Spanish.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Balut is recognized as a national food of the Philippines.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] It is commonly sold as a street food and served as an appetizer in restaurants.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] The taste of balut is similar to chicken soup, and it has an unusual texture.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Balut is found in some countries and locations of North America.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] While it cannot be found in every store in North America, specialty stores such as T&T — and, in particular, Filipino stores in the Greater Vancouver area — often sell balut.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] In the United States, growers such as Metzer Farms specialize in balut production, spreading the knowledge of balut and its awareness.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] One reason it may not be found or consumed as frequently in North America is that the majority of people outside of Southeast Asia still recognize balut as a novel and taboo food and are often anxious about trying it.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] In the Philippines, balut is often eaten with salt or a chili, garlic, and vinegar (white or coconut sap) mixture to season, depending on personal preference.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Balut can be served in many ways and may be cooked, boiled, or fried.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] It may be cooked adobo style, fried in omelets, or used as filling in pastries.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Although balut is globally recognized as a Filipino food, it is being consumed less and less in the Philippines.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] This is partly due to increasingly Western tastes, but also because balut is often associated with poverty.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Some countries and locations will serve balut raw, although this is not a common practice.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] "Raw", in this sense, could mean the balut was lightly boiled or cooked very briefly.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] This is potentially dangerous, since it increases the risk of spoiling and of ingesting harmful microorganisms.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] In Vietnam, balut (trứng vịt lộn, hột vịt lộn) can be found in the majority of breakfast restaurants selling noodles (often as a side dish), and night street vendors.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] It is boiled and then served in small bowls with salt, chili, pepper and ginger.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Balut is considered to be a street food, and like many other street foods, it is best consumed as soon as it is prepared and served.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Sources suggest that at most, the shelf life of a cooked balut is one day, but it can last up to a week in the refrigerator.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] According to the FDA Food Code, balut can perish over time or due to temperature changes.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] After being cooked, balut should be handled either at 57 °C (135 °F) and above or kept at or below 5 °C (41 °F).
[src:balut-food/balut-food] While most countries have specific regulations and standards for food, Canada has certain egg regulations pertaining to what products can be labelled as an egg.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Balut eggs are not subjected to the egg regulations in Canada under the Canadian Food Inspection Agency, meaning they do not require the specific labeling requirements and rules of the traditional chicken egg.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Eating balut is forbidden for some religious groups.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Both Judaism and Islam have strict prohibitions on consuming food that is prepared in manners incompatible with religiously prescribed dietary laws.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] In Judaism, the embryo of a chick inside an egg of a bird, even a kosher bird, is forbidden for consumption.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] The Quran forbids consumption of meat if the animal has not been slaughtered properly, making the animal or animal-product "maytah".
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Because balut is an egg containing a partially developed embryo, this makes it "haram", or "forbidden".
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Information relating to whether boiling a partially developed embryo is ethically acceptable or not can be found in the legislation relating to the euthanasia and treatment of research animals.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Bird embryos that have reached greater than 50% of their incubation have developed a neural tube sufficient for pain perception; therefore, they should be euthanized by similar methods used in avian neonates, such as anesthetic overdose, decapitation, or prolonged exposure to carbon dioxide.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Similarly, in the UK, embryonic birds are "protected animals" once they have reached the last third of their incubation period.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] There are specified methods of humanely killing protected animals used in research, but boiling is not one of these.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Depending on the species of duck, some eggs used for balut would be boiled within the last half or third of embryo development.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Duck embryos are often taken off incubation in order to stunt the growth process; the embryos no longer develop and become readily available for purchasing.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] The RSPCA Australia recommends against boiling the duck embryo from the 18th day of incubation onwards due to the potential for suffering beyond that point, and notes that it is "an area that is yet to be further researched".
[src:balut-food/balut-food] A petition has been raised to get 5,000 signatures to have balut labeled "fertilized duck egg with embryo" and taken off the menu in the Maharlika restaurant, New York.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] As of 2014, the restaurant was selling balut for $5 each.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] As a response to this petition, Filipino New Yorkers have created a counterpetition, asking to leave the food item alone.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] The incubation temperatures and environment required for the proper development of balut during processing are ideal growth conditions for many bacteria, including *Salmonella enteritidis*.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] In addition, faecal pathogens can be deposited on the egg shell surface during laying.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Balut is therefore labelled as a "Hazardous Food" in Canada.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Warnings have been published to obtain balut only from safe, well-known producers.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] In the United States, eggs are sold at Asian markets.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] However, to get the right age eggs and to ensure freshness, it is recommended that they be purchased from a professional or an egg vendor at Asian farmers markets.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] On April 10, 2015, former Pateros mayor Jaime C.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] Medina collaborated with the Center for Culinary Arts (CCA, Manila) and the History Channel to attempt to set the record for the world's largest serving of balut in Pateros, Metro Manila.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] The CCA chefs, headed by Tristan Encarnacion, prepared 1,000 pieces of balut into an adobo dish that was recorded to have weighed 117.5 kilograms.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] The resulting dish was enjoyed by the townsfolk in a symbolic boodle fight, with tables topped with banana leaves stretching along B.
[src:balut-food/balut-food] The 2024 horror video game *Hapunan* has the player taking on the role of Niko, a poor Filipino student who sells balut in Barangay Sak Dudol, where a gang of contract killers is suspected of committing brutal murders during the night.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] The game is named after a delicacy made from the fetal duck egg available in some Southeast Asian countries.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] Edgar "Eddie" Woolbright was an American soldier stationed in the Philippines who remained there for the rest of his life, becoming a successful local businessman.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] The origin story that is recounted for the game by its players is that two U.S. soldiers were in one of Woolbright's early establishments in Tacloban, the Woolbright Tacloban Airline Hotel, stuck for a drinking/gambling game to play because they had no playing cards but wanted to play poker.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] They settled on playing poker with dice rather than cards, inventing what they initially called "poker dice".
[src:balut-food/balut-game] Originally the game's format only extended to two players, but some Europeans staying at the same hotel who also wanted to play extended the game to more than two players.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] The "poker dice" game gained its current name when Woolbright and some players out on a walk one day, hearing the cries of "balut!" by balut egg vendors, decided that that would be the name of the game.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] Woolbright took the game from Tacloban to his later establishments in the Philippines as his businesses grew, and also played it at the British Club in Cebu City.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] Other people exported it elsewhere: a British captain to Singapore, and some expatriate Scandinavians to Thailand.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] An International Balut Federation was created in 1972.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] The international Danish community has taken the game as a popular method of social interaction abroad and at home, with Danish expatriates/businessmen gathering to play the game monthly.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] Rules of the game, code of conduct including dress code are enforced by participants and by the gamemasters, and games are organized by members of the International Balut Federation, or IBF.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] The game involves rolling five dice up to 3 times to make various combinations, which are noted on a scorecard.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] A *Balut* is a five-of-a-kind of any denomination, but unlike in Yahtzee it counts for little in terms of points.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] Players who obtain a *Balut* announce it to the other players by calling out "Balut!" – similar to calling out "Bingo!", and note it on a special scorecard.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] Players try to guess before gameplay how many Baluts will be made during the game; correctly guessing the total number can earn a prize.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] On a turn, player may roll the dice up to three times.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] After a roll, player may take one or more dice out of play to save their result and then roll the remaining dice.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] There are seven scoring combinations that the player may only achieve once.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] At the end of the turn, the player will score per the combo created.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] If the player cannot create a combo, then player must scratch one of their remaining unfulfilled combos.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] That scratched combo is no longer playable for the remainder of the game.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] Play then continues to the left until all players have completed the 7 combo possibilities with a score or a scratch.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] Further rounds may be played...high score wins.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] In 1973, the game was brought into Singapore and a set of rules was established at Singapore Town Club in 1978.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] This set of rules was later spread to other private clubs in Singapore and to other Southeast Asian countries such as Malaysia, Thailand and Philippines.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] Although the Singapore Town Club ceased existence in 2000 other clubs continue the name for the tournament.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] These Clubs organize regular local and international tournaments as well as gathering together each year for the STC Balut Interport Championship.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] The 28th was held at the British Club Bangkok in 2008 and the 29th was held at the Sabah Golf & Country Club in 2009.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] In 2017 the international competition was held at the Sarawak Club in Kuching, Sarawak, Malaysia.
[src:balut-food/balut-game] In 2010 the 30th STC Interport Competition was held at the British Club Bangkok on 19 to 21 November.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] A **bird egg** is the reproductive structure produced by female birds, consisting of a hard, calcareous shell that encloses nutrient-dense yolk, protective albumen, and embryonic membranes, providing a self-contained environment for embryonic development and hatching.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Bird eggs range in quantity from one (as in condors) to up to seventeen (the grey partridge).
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Clutch size may vary latitudinally within a species.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Some birds lay eggs even when the eggs have not been fertilized; it is not uncommon for pet owners to find their lone bird nesting on a clutch of infertile eggs, which are sometimes called wind-eggs.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] The default color of vertebrate eggs is the white of the calcium carbonate from which the shells are made, but some birds, mainly passerines, produce colored eggs.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] The pigments biliverdin and its zinc chelate give a green or blue ground color, and protoporphyrin produces reds and browns as a ground color or as spotting.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Non-passerines typically have white eggs, except in some ground-nesting groups, such as the Charadriiformes, sandgrouse and nightjars, where camouflage is necessary, and some parasitic cuckoos, which lay eggs that often closely match the passerine host's egg.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] To varying degrees of success, host passerine species have combined speckles, blotches and other egg markings with visual pattern-recognition abilities to help them reject cuckoos' counterfeit eggs.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Most other passerines, in contrast, lay colored eggs, even if there is no need of cryptic colors.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] However, the photographic markings on passerine eggs have been suggested to reduce brittleness by acting as a solid state lubricant.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] If insufficient calcium is available in the local soil, the egg shell may be thin, especially in a circle around the broad end.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Protoporphyrin speckling compensates for this, and increases inversely to the amount of calcium in the soil.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] To understand the functional significance of eggshell spotting (or maculation) it is important to quantify this pigmentation For the same reason, later eggs in a clutch are more spotted than early ones, as the female's store of calcium is depleted.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Birds which build in trees generally have blue or greenish eggs, either spotted or unspotted, while birds that build in bushes or near or on the ground are likely to lay speckled eggs.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] The color of individual eggs is also genetically influenced, and appears to be inherited through the mother only, suggesting the gene responsible for pigmentation is on the female-specific W chromosome (female birds are WZ, males are ZZ).
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Color was once thought to be applied to the shell immediately before laying, but this research shows coloration is an integral part of the development of the shell, with the same protein responsible for depositing calcium carbonate, or protoporphyrins when there is a lack of that mineral.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] In species such as the common guillemot, which nest in large groups, each female's eggs have very different markings, making it easier for females to identify their own eggs on the crowded cliff ledges on which they breed.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Tiny pores in a bird eggshell allow the embryo to breathe.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] The domestic hen's egg has around 7500 pores.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] The shape of eggs varies considerably across bird species, ranging from near-spherical (such as those of the little bee-eater) to highly pyriform or conical (such as those of the common murre) with the familiar shape of the chicken egg lying in between.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Early scientific investigators of egg shape suggested that the oval shape of eggs was caused by the egg being forced through the oviduct by peristalsis.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] The calcification of the egg in the shell gland/uterus then fixes it in this shape, and the egg is laid with the blunt end appearing first (for a diagram showing the different sections of the bird oviduct, see here).
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] These observations cannot be explained by peristalsis.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] It has been proposed that the egg acquires its shape (with the pointed egg caudal) as it is forced through the narrow isthmus, but this assertion has not been thoroughly verified.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Cliff-nesting birds often have highly conical eggs.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] They are less likely to roll off, tending instead to roll around in a tight circle; this trait is likely to have arisen due to evolution via natural selection.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] In contrast, many hole-nesting birds have nearly spherical eggs.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] A pointed egg will tend to sit on its side, with the big end tipped upward.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] The big end contains the air sac and its shell is pierced by a higher density of pores than the more pointed end.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Tipping the big end upwards improves oxygen flow to the large head, with the physiologically demanding eyes and brain, that develops in the big end while the tail develops at the more pointed end.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] In a 2017 publication in the journal *Science*, mathematical modeling of 50,000 bird eggs data showed that bird egg shape is a product of flight adaptations and not the outcome of nesting conditions or a bird's life history.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] A strong correlation was found between egg shape and flight ability on broad taxonomic scales, such that birds engaging in high powered flights usually maximize egg size by having elliptical shaped eggs while maintaining a streamlined body plan.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Selection acting during incubation, such as breeding site and incubation posture, are also thought to influence egg-shape variation across birds.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Egg size tends to be proportional to the size of the adult bird, from the half gram egg of the bee hummingbird to the 1.5 kg egg of the ostrich.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Kiwis have disproportionately large eggs, up to 20% of the female's body weight.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] This evolutionary trait results in kiwi chicks that can emerge from the nest days after hatching, ready to start foraging for food.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] The number of eggs laid in a single brood is referred to as the clutch.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Clutch size is usually within a small range of variation.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Some birds respond to the accidental loss of eggs by laying a replacement egg.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Others will stop laying based on the apparent size of the clutch.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] According to whether they respond to addition, removal, or both addition and removal of eggs, birds are classified as determinate layers (number of eggs laid is predetermined and do not respond to change) or as indeterminate layers.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] In general, birds with small clutch size tended to be indeterminate.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] For example, the principal predators of the black oystercatcher's eggs include raccoons, skunks, mink, river and sea otters, gulls, crows and foxes.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] The stoat (*Mustela erminea*) and long-tailed weasel (*Neogale frenata*) steal ducks' eggs.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Ostrich eggs are vulnerable to many predators ranging from mongooses and Egyptian vultures, to hyenas.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Snakes of the genera *Dasypeltis* and *Elachistodon* specialize in eating eggs.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Humans have a long history of eating eggs, both wild bird eggs and farm-raised bird eggs.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Brood parasitism occurs in birds when one species lays its eggs in the nest of another.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] In some cases, the host's eggs are removed or eaten by the female, or expelled by her chick.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Brood parasites include cowbirds, honeyguides, and many Old World cuckoos.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Today, the hard shells of bird eggs are unique among animals.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] However, this trait evolved in dinosaurs, the larger group to which birds belong.
[src:balut-food/bird-egg] Eggs of the modern type, with an inner mammillary, more outer prismatic and an outer crystalline layer, appear during the Jurassic and are associated with fossils of the Maniraptora.
[src:balut-food/bizarre-foods-with-andrew-zimmern-p01] Originally a one-hour documentary titled *Bizarre Foods of Asia*, repeated showings on the Travel Channel drew consistent, considerable audiences.
[src:balut-food/bizarre-foods-with-andrew-zimmern-p01] In late 2006, TLC decided to turn the documentary into a weekly, one-hour show with the same premise and with Zimmern as the host.
[src:balut-food/bizarre-foods-with-andrew-zimmern-p01] In 2009, Zimmern took a break from *Bizarre Foods* to work on one season of the spin-off *Bizarre World*.
[src:balut-food/bizarre-foods-with-andrew-zimmern-p01] Beginning with Season 7, the show has been retitled Bizarre Foods America.
[src:balut-food/bizarre-foods-with-andrew-zimmern-p01] The format remains the same but focuses more on the United States rather than international travel.
[src:balut-food/bizarre-foods-with-andrew-zimmern-p01] Starting with season 12, Bizarre Foods America has episodes in the other countries of the Americas.
[src:balut-food/bizarre-foods-with-andrew-zimmern-p01] New episodes have been shot in Cartagena, Colombia; Lima, Peru; Ft.
[src:balut-food/bizarre-foods-with-andrew-zimmern-p01] Worth, Texas; Copper River (Alaska); Nashville, Tennessee; Atlanta, Georgia; the Florida Keys; and Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada.
[src:balut-food/bizarre-foods-with-andrew-zimmern-p01] A spin-off series of half-hour episodes that focused on famed destinations' classic foods—where they came from, how they're prepared, and the best way to enjoy them.
[src:balut-food/bizarre-foods-with-andrew-zimmern-p01] Focused on general fare and not bizarre foods.
[src:balut-food/bizarre-foods-with-andrew-zimmern-p02] A DVD set (2 discs) called *Bizarre Foods with Andrew Zimmern: Collection 1* was released on January 8, 2008.
[src:balut-food/bizarre-foods-with-andrew-zimmern-p02] A second DVD set (2 discs) called *Bizarre Foods with Andrew Zimmern: Collection 2* was released on October 7, 2008.
